sequence, so you should include this also in the user manual as a separate section on software maintenance.\n\n<span style=\"font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">This section does not, nor did any part of the lectures or class notes covered, indicate that there needs to be a change log for the software updates/maintenance, however, after class on Monday, you indicated that you wanted to see a change log for software updates.\n\nI do not think it is fair to us to be graded against something that we were not instructed on.</span></pre>','','@'),(221,'A',220,3,1,3,NULL,0,NULL,2,NULL,1204735120,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2011-12-12 22:42:42',NULL,NULL,'Your project will be graded according to the above criterion.   When you asked what additional information one can provide in dealing with software maintenance, I answered the usual way is to have \"change orders\", which are very similar to the test plan entries.   This is in order to explain the common way for software maintenance.',NULL,'@'),(222,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,51,NULL,2184285158,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,2045925636,21,1.2927e+10,0,'','2012-01-18 14:29:37',NULL,'Welcome to CS1635','','','@'),(223,'A_HIDDEN',222,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,80,NULL,1136264818,1,1626114849,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-01-21 19:59:32','2012-01-22 12:37:45',NULL,'Thank you very much Jing Tao',NULL,'@'),(224,'Q_HIDDEN',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,80,NULL,1136264818,1,1626114849,0,0,0,1626114849,10,1.29784e+10,0,'','2012-01-21 20:00:10','2012-01-22 12:37:45','How much wood would a wood chuck chuck','if a wood chuck could chuck wood?','','@'),(225,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,1,NULL,30,NULL,2530493879,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,1651500030,19,1.30312e+10,0,'','2012-01-23 18:01:40',NULL,'Group Brainstorm Ideas List','Do we have to describe the ideas we generated? Or we need to list only the names of the ideas?','','@'),(226,'A',225,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,51,NULL,2184306040,NULL,NULL,1,0,1,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-01-23 18:11:22',NULL,NULL,'Yes, you need to describe it with one or two lines of plain English.  The basic idea is - you need to let other people (e.g. the instructor or the TA), who didn\'t join your brainstorming sessions, figure out what your ideas are through the document you provided.',NULL,'@'),(227,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,74,NULL,1651500030,NULL,NULL,4,0,4,2992331112,26,1.31296e+10,0,'','2012-01-26 12:09:35',NULL,'onTouchListener Problem','So this isn\'t really a question but I had a problem where the onTouchListener was only \"Seeing\" ACTION_DOWN(press mouse button) events and not a ACTION_MOVE(from dragging the mouse) or a ACTION_UP(release mouse button).  \n\nTo solve this you HAVE to return true from your onTouch() method.  I\'m not sure what the parent components are doing that stops the other events from firing but clearly they are.','','@'),(228,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,1,NULL,73,NULL,1626015101,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,1283313715,16,1.33785e+10,0,'','2012-01-26 20:21:57',NULL,'Python GUI Issue','I got the following errors after trying to run the python program using command-line. I don\'t know if it\'s a version problem, I have python2.6.\n\nTraceback (most recent call last):\nFile \"C:\\Users\\Jc\\Documents\\Pitt\\Spring 2012\\CS1635-Interface Methology\\HW\\assign2.py\", line 114, in <module>\n    app = Application(master=root)\n\nFile \"C:\\Users\\Jc\\Documents\\Pitt\\Spring 2012\\CS1635-Interface Methology\\HW\\assign2.py\", line 107,\nin __init__\n    self.create_widgets()\n\nFile \"C:\\Users\\Jc\\Documents\\Pitt\\Spring 2012\\CS1635-Interface Methology\\HW\\assign2.py\", line 98, in create_widgets\n    self.writing_canvas.bind(\"\", self.mouse_down)\n\nFile \"C:\\Python26\\lib\\lib-tk\\Tkinter.py\", line 985, in bind\n    return self._bind((\'bind\', self._w), sequence, func, add)\nFile \"C:\\Python26\\lib\\lib-tk\\Tkinter.py\", line 940, in _bind\n    self.tk.call(what + (sequence, cmd))\n_tkinter.TclError: no events specified in binding','','@'),(229,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,1,NULL,23,NULL,1204253369,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,1651500030,17,1.31773e+10,0,'','2012-01-31 22:18:24',NULL,'Getting the response from the server.','So I\'m trying to test if my app works but I have no idea if there\'s an issue with my HTTP POST or if I\'m using the wrong info from the response. I originally used getEntity but whenever I tried to print the contents, it was null. I noticed that under the \"Server response\" section of the assignment info, it says something about the HTTP Header so I tried to see what was in the header and it gave me text/html instead of text/plain.\n\nAnother question I had is with the parameters. In the python script and the example website\'s javascript, it had the api key as the second parameter and the q as the first parameter. Is this supposed to be the same in the Android version or should it be as it\'s posted in the assignment info (key first, q second).\n\nFinally, when we pass the q, is the string supposed to be formatted as [x,x,x,x] or x,x,x,x.','','@'),(230,'A',229,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,38,NULL,2184306080,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'html','2012-02-01 13:50:22',NULL,NULL,'<p>\n	1. For some reason, the URL used for English only produces a text/html response. Try the other URL (<tt>http://cwritepad.appspot.com/reco/gb2312).</tt></p>\n<p>\n	2. The server should accept the POST paramenters in any order.</p>\n<p>\n	3. The format is <span class=\"entry-content\">[x,x,x,x]</span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>',NULL,NULL),(231,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,1,NULL,75,NULL,1283313715,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,1204253516,13,1.31922e+10,0,'','2012-02-02 01:21:06',NULL,'modifying an object from a different Activity','The first Activity creates and runs the fullscreen canvas and I have another Activity for the \"options\" screen.  I have the clear button on the options screen (the second activity) and I\'m trying to give it an onclick listener for the button press to clear the canvas that has one line of code:\n\nCanvas.drawColor(Color.BLACK);\n\n  However, I\'m getting the error \"Cannot make a static reference to the non-static method drawColor(int) from the type Canvas\".\n\nI think this is because the Canvas object/view is created in one Activity and the onClick method/listener is in a different activity, so it doesn\'t know the canvas exists.  Is that the reason and how do I get this situation to work?','','@'),(232,'A',231,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,23,NULL,2184287688,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'html','2012-02-02 08:46:04',NULL,NULL,'<p>\n	First: On a design standpoint, I don\'t think you should be having main functions like clear on the options screen, it should be on the same activity as the Canvas.</p>\n<p>\n	Second: You\'re sort of right.&nbsp;<a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/290884/what-is-the-reason-behind-non-static-method-cannot-be-referenced-from-a-static\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/290884/what-is-the-reason-behind-non-static-method-cannot-be-referenced-from-a-static</a></p>',NULL,NULL),(233,'C',232,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,75,NULL,1283313715,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-02 10:01:34',NULL,NULL,'ha, when searching for an answer, that was the main result I found.  But most of the answers said it\'s because the method isn\'t static.  However, I thought using static methods was a bad practice that was commonly overused, so I kept looking.   I couldn\'t find a direct answer for the proper way to do this.  \nThe idea for the options screen came from our project description page that says \"One way to satisfy the application functionality requirements is to create an application with two views: one of the canvas, and another of an options screen that lets the user change modes and adjust settings.\"  But then again, I don\'t think I implemented my canvas as expected and will review that.\n\nHowever, I have a feeling I will run into the same issue when I start implementing other options on the options screen.',NULL,'@'),(234,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,1,NULL,53,NULL,1813077573,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,1283313715,9,1.34669e+10,0,'','2012-02-06 09:47:55',NULL,'Restoring objects after screen rotation','I have an ArrayList of Objects that I use store point information (points drawn on the screen). When I rotate the device, my instance data is lost so I am using onSaveInstanceState to store/restore the primitive types; however, it doesn\'t seem so easy for restoring objects. I read in some forums that one could use Parceable or Serializable objects. Is this the best approach or am I missing something more obvious?','','@'),(235,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,2,NULL,75,NULL,1283313715,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,1135296534,10,1.34625e+10,0,'','2012-02-15 18:50:02',NULL,'Cocos2dx Setup Error: Can\'t find VC2008 or VC2010 installed!','I\'m trying to get Cocos2dx setup and I\'m stuck on one of the initial steps.  I\'m following this guide here: http://www.multigesture.net/articles/how-to-setup-cocos2d-x-windows-and-android/\n\nI\'ve gotten as far as downloading the cocos zip (cocos2d-1.0.1-x-0.11.0.Zip), extracting it, and then trying to run \"build-win32.bat\".  I keep getting the error:\n\"Can\'t find VC2008 or VC2010 installed!\"\n\nI thought this was referring to the vc++ 2010 Redistributable Package, but I have them installed.  I haven\'t been able to find a definite cause or solution searching online.  I\'m wondering if it\'s because I\'m running Windows 7 64 bit and if it\'s not going to work on a 64bit machine.\n\nWhy I\'m getting this error?  Did anyone have this problem setting up on their Windows 7 64bit machine?','','@'),(236,'A',235,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,38,NULL,2184306080,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'html','2012-02-15 21:37:01',NULL,NULL,'<p>\n	<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: times new roman,times,serif;\">You can build Cocos2d-x projects for Android without running build-win32.bat. Please try the following.</span></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: times new roman,times,serif;\">1. Download <span class=\"entry-content\">cocos2d-1.0.1-x-0.11.0.Zip from </span>http://www.cocos2d-x.org/projects/cocos2d-x/wiki/Download and extract to a permanent location.</span></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: times new roman,times,serif;\">2. Download Android ndk and extract to permanent location.</span></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: times new roman,times,serif;\">3. Add those two directories to your PATH</span></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: times new roman,times,serif;\">4. If using Windows, install Cygwin with gcc, g++, GNU Make, and GNU AWK.</span></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: times new roman,times,serif;\">If using MAC, install gcc, g++, GNU Make and GNU AWK via Xcode (if not already installed).</span></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: times new roman,times,serif;\">5. Locate a script called \"create-android-project.bash\" (Windows) or&nbsp;</span></span></p>\n<pre>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: times new roman,times,serif;\">\"create-android-project.sh\"(Unix) in your root cocos2d-x directory. This script creates\na base HelloWorld cocos2d-x project. Before you can use it, you must modify the\ncreate-android-project script to reflect the path of your Cygwin/bin, Android SDK, and\nNDK installations. The comments within the file will guide you.\n\n<strong>[steps 6-8 are covered in a tutorial on the cocos2d-x website.\n(Scroll down to Ch.4 Android)\nhttp://www.cocos2d-x.org/projects/cocos2d-x/wiki/Chapter_1_-_How_to_Create_a_New_cocos2d-x_project_on_multi-platforms]</strong>\n\n6. Now, run create-android-project. It will ask for a package name, project name, and target\nAndroid SDK installation. It will create your project in the root cocos2d-x directory.\n\n7. Once the project creation script finishes, you are ready to compile the native c++ code\nlocated in projectdirectory/Classes and in projectdirectory/Android/jni/helloworld.\nThe \"build_native.sh\" shell script will automatically do this. Run this script. If using Windows,\nrun this script via Cygwin terminal.\n\n8. When this script completes, you can import your project into Eclipse by\ncreating a new Android project from existing source.\n\n9. Use the Eclipse run command to run the Cocos2d-x HelloWorld\napplication.\n\n\nI understand that some of you are encountering \"permission denied\" errors\non Win7. Try turning of UAC as described here.\n</span></span>http://www.mydigitallife.info/how-to-disable-and-turn-off-uac-in-windows-7/\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: times new roman,times,serif;\">That will not always solve the problem. I am currently looking searching for\nother solutions.\n</span></span></pre>',NULL,'@'),(237,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,1,238,74,NULL,1651500030,NULL,NULL,1,0,1,1136270530,7,1.348e+10,0,'html','2012-02-18 01:27:29',NULL,'Samsung Galaxy Driver problem','<p>\n	After an awful night of trying to install the drivers for the Samsung Galaxy Player this is my solution:</p>\n<p>\n	Before I start, I am running Windows 7 Ultimate 64bit SP1 (Ultimate my ass) so it is possible that this is only a 64bit problem.</p>\n<ol>\n	<li>\n		&nbsp;Set the Galaxy Player to debug mode (this is on the Galaxy Player):\n		<ol>\n			<li>\n				Settings &gt; Applications &gt; Select Unknown Sources</li>\n			<li>\n				Settings &gt; Applications &gt; Development &gt; Select USB debugging mode</li>\n		</ol>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Now when you plug the USB into your computer you should see &nbsp;the device in your device manager under:\n		<ol>\n			<li>\n				Other &gt; YP-G1&nbsp;</li>\n			<li>\n				Other &gt; CDC Serial</li>\n		</ol>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		This link&nbsp;<a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://developer.android.com/sdk/win-usb.html\">http://developer.android.com/sdk/win-usb.html</a>&nbsp;has the drivers for Windows.</li>\n	<li>\n		Even though it says that the drivers you get from downloading through the Android SDK manager support the G1 it doesn\'t. At least not mine ( I have version 4).</li>\n	<li>\n		The link says that the downloaded drivers should be in <span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&lt;your skd folder&gt;\\extras\\google\\usb_driver</span></li>\n	<li>\n		navigate there and open android_winusb.inf\n		<ol>\n			<li>\n				&nbsp;I had to open my editor as administrator, then open the file through there but I my SDK is in Program Files so if you store it elsewhere it may not be an issue.</li>\n		</ol>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		add these lines under&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">[Google.NTx86] </span>and under<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp;[Google.NTamd64]</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<blockquote>\n	<div>\n		<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">;</span></div>\n	<div>\n		<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">;YP-G1</span></div>\n	<div>\n		&nbsp;</div>\n	<div>\n		<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">%CompositeAdbInterface% &nbsp; &nbsp; = USB_Install, USB\\VID_04E8&amp;PID_685E&amp;REV_0400&amp;MI_03</span></div>\n	<div>\n		&nbsp;</div>\n	<div>\n		<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">%SingleAdbInterface% <span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span> &nbsp; &nbsp;= USB_Install, USB\\VID_04E8&amp;PID_685E&amp;MI_03</span></div>\n</blockquote>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;8. Now just update the driver as you would normally, from&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: \'courier new\', courier, monospace;\">&lt;your skd folder&gt;\\extras\\google\\usb_driver</span></div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	I didn\'t bother with the CDC serial device because I was able to then see the device in adb and install .apks on it. &nbsp;If you can\'t get a hold of the drivers let me know and I can zip up my extras folder and post it on the wiki.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<span style=\"color: rgb(178, 34, 34);\">Lastly, I pulled some of these instructions from the web but the last part with the driver I pulled out of my ass. &nbsp;So it\'s on you if you want to try this method. &nbsp;It worked for me but I can\'t&nbsp;</span><span style=\"color:#b22222;\">guarantee</span><span style=\"color: rgb(178, 34, 34);\">&nbsp;the same for you. &nbsp;I don\'t know anything about windows drivers so if your computer melts or does a \'Han Solo in Carbonite\' impression it\'s not my fault.</span></div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Thaddeus Taylor</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>','','@'),(238,'A',237,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,75,NULL,1283313715,75,1283313715,1,0,1,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-18 02:15:53','2012-02-18 05:12:51',NULL,'I had similar trouble getting my Galaxy S phone\'s usb drivers.  Instructions said to use the Google usb drivers available for download through the Android SDK (just like you describe), but those drivers didn\'t work for me either.  I found the usb drivers were really only available as part of Samsung\'s Kies software install.  I kept searching and found a thread at xda-developers.com where they have separated the usb drivers and posted them as a stand-alone install.\n\nhttp://forum.xda-developers.com/showthread.php?t=961956\n\nIt says the drivers are for all Samsung Android phones.  I know that\'s technically not a phone, but I bet it uses the same usb drivers.',NULL,'@'),(239,'C',238,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,74,NULL,1651500030,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-18 02:50:31',NULL,NULL,'Cool man.  I am inherently mistrustful of \'drivers\' from forums, still I never found that one.',NULL,'@'),(240,'C',236,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,75,NULL,1283313715,75,1283313715,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-18 04:33:48','2012-02-18 05:04:08',NULL,'I moved the comment that I made here to an \"answer\".  I\'m only able to edit my comment, not delete it.  Thanks for all the help, Stephen.',NULL,'@'),(241,'A',235,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,75,NULL,1283313715,75,1283313715,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'html','2012-02-18 04:59:07','2012-02-26 19:18:25',NULL,'<p>\n	<span class=\"qa-c-item-content\"><span class=\"entry-content\">After going through so much trouble getting my environment setup in Windows 7 (x64), I thought I\'d make one guide that should take you step by step to a working setup. &nbsp;Stephen was a huge help and I\'m basically going to copy his steps above and edit to match what I did. &nbsp;Hopefully I\'ll be able to edit this post, in case I need to clarify or add more in the future.<br>\n	<br>\n	This was written with Windows 7 (x64) in mind and starting from the software setup the class has required so far. (Eclipse, Android SDK, etc). &nbsp;You will need to install three more pieces of software.<br>\n	<br>\n	The Android NDK (<a href=\"http://developer.android.com/sdk/ndk/index.html%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://developer.android.com/sdk/ndk/index.html)</a><br>\n	Cocos2d-x (<a href=\"http://www.cocos2d-x.org/projects/cocos2d-x/wiki/Download%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.cocos2d-x.org/projects/cocos2d-x/wiki/Download)</a><br>\n	Cygwin (<a href=\"http://www.cygwin.com/%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.cygwin.com/)</a><br>\n	<br>\n	<br>\n	1. Extract Cocos2d-x and place its directory somewhere where you have full permissions. &nbsp;I chose c:\\Users\\\"YourAccountName\"\\.<br>\n	<br>\n	2. Extract the Android NDK to a directory where you have full permissions.<br>\n	<br>\n	3. Add those two directories to your PATH.<br>\n	<br>\n	4. If using Windows, install Cygwin with gcc, g++, GNU Make, and GNU AWK.<br>\n	If using MAC, install gcc, g++, GNU Make and GNU AWK via Xcode (if not already installed).<br>\n	<br>\n	5. In your Cocos2d-x directory, find \"create-android-project.bat\" (Windows) or \"create-android-project.sh (Unix). &nbsp;Edit this script\'s references to the the Cygwin\\bin, Android SDK tools, and NDK directories so they match your setup. &nbsp;Its comments will guide you.<br>\n	<br>\n	6. Now you can run \"create-android-project.bat\" to create an android project. It will ask for a package name, project name, and target Android SDK installation. &nbsp;The project directory will be created in the Cocos2d-x directory and it will be named after your project.<br>\n	<br>\n	7. Once the project creation script finishes, you can compile the native c++ code located in projectdirectory/Classes and in projectdirectory/Android/jni/helloworld by using the build_native.sh script. &nbsp;To do this in Windows, open Cygwin, navigate to your project\'s \"android\" directory, and type \"./build_native.sh\" to run the script.<br>\n	<br>\n	8. When this script completes, import your project into Eclipse. &nbsp;Do this by creating a new Android project, select \"Create from existing source\" and set the location as your project\'s \"android\" directory.</span></span><br>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	9. In Eclipse, you\'ll notice some errors in a couple of the source files for org.cocos2dx.lib.&nbsp; You need to remove the Overrides.&nbsp; An easy way to do this is open each file, ctrl+f to find \"Override\" then Replace All with \"//Override\".</p>\n<p>\n	<br>\n	<span class=\"qa-c-item-content\"><span class=\"entry-content\">10. Now you should be good to go.&nbsp; Run the project in Eclipse and you will see the Cocos2d-x logo in the emulator.<br>\n	<br>\n	<br>\n	Additional Notes:<br>\n	<br>\n	Permissions issues:<br>\n	If you run into permissions issues, don\'t try to manually correct permissions as they come up. &nbsp;You will have to correct them everytime a file is created or overwritten by the scripts. &nbsp;Instead alleviate the entire issue by putting the NDK and Cocos2d-x directories where you have full permissions, such as your user directory.<br>\n	<br>\n	Can\'t delete a directory or file in Windows:<br>\n	Use Cygwin to delete the file or directory (rm or rmdir commands).<br>\n	<br>\n	\"awk.exe is outdated\" error:</span></span><br>\n	<span class=\"qa-c-item-content\"><span class=\"entry-content\">This is fixed in version 7b.&nbsp; If you can\'t update, go to android-ndk\\prebuilt\\windows\\bin and rename \"awk.exe\" to \"awk_old.exe\".&nbsp; Renaming it hides it from a script and causes cygwin to fallback to a built in version that works.</span></span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	Black screen in emulator:</p>\n<p>\n	It\'s a bug in the 2.2 emulator.&nbsp; Create a new avd using 2.3 or later.</p>',NULL,'@'),(242,'C',241,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,75,NULL,1283313715,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-18 05:29:59',NULL,NULL,'Android NDK 7b was just released the past day or so.  According to the changelog, a couple issues that I\'ve run into already are fixed:  The awk issue and the creation of undeletable NUL files.',NULL,'@'),(243,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,1,NULL,53,NULL,1813077573,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,411246587,7,1.34855e+10,0,'','2012-02-19 07:41:20',NULL,'Group Assig #3: Method question','In the description for the Method section of assignment #3, it states we are required to write a 1 page description of the \"Tasks\". That section mentions that each team member is to be assigned a \"task\" (greeter, computer. etc..). But is the 1 page description of \"Tasks\" referring to those tasks (roles) or the 3 task we chose to experiment with our users? I\'m only asking because 1 page seems like a lot for the roles but it does make sense for 3 tasks.','','@'),(244,'A',243,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,53,NULL,1813077573,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'html','2012-02-19 07:47:45',NULL,NULL,'<p>\n	I think I just answered my own question after reading it a few more times.&nbsp;<br>\n	<br>\n	\"<b id=\"internal-source-marker_0.17523231683298945\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; font-weight: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Describe some details of your testing procedure. This should include the roles of each member of the team. To prepare for the experiment, you should assign team members to the</span></b><b style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; font-weight: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><em> </em></span></b><em><b style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; font-weight: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">different tasks</span></b></em><b style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13px; font-family: Arial; font-weight: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (i.e., greeter, computer, facilitator, observer, etc.) and practice with someone playing the participant.\"</span></b></p>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"font-family: Arial; color: #000000; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre-wrap;\">It looks like the roles should be included in the \"Details\" paragraph of \"Method\" and Tasks (easy, medium, hard) is the 1 page item.</span></span></p>',NULL,'@'),(245,'C',238,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,75,NULL,1283313715,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-21 14:20:12',NULL,NULL,'For those curious, we connected the Samsung Galaxy Player to my laptop with these drivers installed and the device was recognized.',NULL,'@'),(246,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,1,NULL,74,NULL,1651500030,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,2992331112,18,1.35897e+10,0,'html','2012-02-24 15:35:41',NULL,'[Cocos2d] Touch crashes app in simpleGame Tutorial','<p>\n	I had a problem when doing the simple game tutorial on the Cocos2d website that touching anywhere on the screen would crash the app. &nbsp;Even at the first step of the tutorial that just shows the HelloWorld text. &nbsp;The only thing that should accept touch input is the small \"power\" icon in the lower right. &nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	I found the solution on the cocos2d forums but it was buried under another title. Basically this is all that has to happen:</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"color: rgb(72, 72, 72); font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;\">\n	Change Application.mk in APP_ROOT/android/jni.&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"color: rgb(72, 72, 72); font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;\">\n	change&nbsp;</p>\n<pre style=\"margin-right: 1em; margin-left: 1.6em; padding-top: 2px; padding-right: 2px; padding-bottom: 2px; padding-left: 0px; border-top-width: 1px; border-right-width: 1px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-left-width: 1px; border-top-style: solid; border-right-style: solid; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: solid; border-top-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-right-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-bottom-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-left-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-image: initial; width: auto; overflow-x: auto; overflow-y: hidden; color: rgb(72, 72, 72);\">\nAPP_STL := stlport_static</pre>\n<p>\n	<span style=\"color: rgb(72, 72, 72); font-family: Verdana, sans-serif;\">to&nbsp;</span></p>\n<pre style=\"margin-right: 1em; margin-left: 1.6em; padding-top: 2px; padding-right: 2px; padding-bottom: 2px; padding-left: 0px; border-top-width: 1px; border-right-width: 1px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-left-width: 1px; border-top-style: solid; border-right-style: solid; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: solid; border-top-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-right-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-bottom-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-left-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-image: initial; width: auto; overflow-x: auto; overflow-y: hidden; color: rgb(72, 72, 72);\">\nAPP_STL := gnustl_static\n</pre>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>','',NULL),(247,'A',246,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,78,NULL,2530477042,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-25 13:00:19',NULL,NULL,'Sorry to hijiack, but I tried this and it didn\'t fix the issue.  After changing that Application.mk, do I have to run build_native.sh again?  Do I then have to re-import it to my Eclipse project, or can I just edit the file directly and re-run the project?\n\n \n\nThanks',NULL,'@'),(248,'C',247,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,74,NULL,1651500030,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-25 14:41:04',NULL,NULL,'Yes rebuild it using the script.  But you shouldn\'t have to re-import it.',NULL,'@'),(249,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,1,250,74,NULL,1651500030,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,2530477010,19,1.36003e+10,0,'html','2012-02-25 16:02:46',NULL,'[Box2d] Can\'t get Box2d to build in cygwin','<p>\n	Ok I want to build the shared library of Box2d to use with my program.</p>\n<p>\n	I\'m not sure how to just build using the Android.mk file.</p>\n<p>\n	Or how to call this Android.mk file from my project.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	I tried downloading the Box2d library&nbsp;<a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://code.google.com/p/box2d/downloads/list\">http://code.google.com/p/box2d/downloads/list</a>&nbsp;version 2.2.1 and building it in cygwin with cmake and make. &nbsp;But it says I don\'t have the open gl libraries when I run cmake:</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<blockquote>\n	<div>\n		<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">CMake Error at /usr/share/cmake-2.8.4/Modules/FindPackageHandleStandardArgs.cmake:91 (MESSAGE):</span></div>\n	<div>\n		<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffff00;\">&nbsp; Could NOT find OpenGL (missing: OPENGL_gl_LIBRARY)</span></span></div>\n	<div>\n		<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">Call Stack (most recent call first):</span></div>\n	<div>\n		<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp; /usr/share/cmake-2.8.4/Modules/FindPackageHandleStandardArgs.cmake:252 (_FPHSA_FAILURE_MESSAGE)</span></div>\n	<div>\n		<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp; /usr/share/cmake-2.8.4/Modules/FindOpenGL.cmake:153 (FIND_PACKAGE_HANDLE_STANDARD_ARGS)</span></div>\n	<div>\n		<span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp; CMakeLists.txt:27 (find_package)</span></div>\n</blockquote>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<span style=\"font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">but I did install everything openGL I could find in the cygwin setup but I couldn\'t find the libraries in /usr/lib or /usr/local/lib.</span></div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Any help would be appreciated.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Thaddeus</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>','','@'),(250,'A',249,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,38,NULL,411246587,38,411246587,2,0,2,NULL,0,NULL,0,'html','2012-02-25 17:08:12','2012-02-26 21:22:48',NULL,'<p>\n	First of all, the Box2D library is alredy included in the root cocos2d-x directory; no need to download.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	To build the Box2d library along with the HelloWorld application:</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	1. Modify ProjectName/Classes/Android.mk as follows ( see highlighted line)</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	LOCAL_C_INCLUDES := $(LOCAL_PATH)/../../cocos2dx \\<br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $(LOCAL_PATH)/../../cocos2dx/platform \\<br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $(LOCAL_PATH)/../../cocos2dx/include \\<br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $(LOCAL_PATH)/../../CocosDenshion/include \\<br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $(LOCAL_PATH)/../../cocos2dx/lua_support \\<br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span style=\"background-color:#ffff00;\">$(LOCAL_PATH)/../../Box2D</span> \\</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span style=\"background-color:#ffff00;\">$(LOCAL_PATH)/../../</span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	LOCAL_LDLIBS := -L$(call host-path, $(LOCAL_PATH)/../android/libs/$(TARGET_ARCH_ABI)) \\<br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -lcocos2d -lcocosdenshion<span style=\"background-color:#ffff00;\"> -lGLESv1_CM -box2d</span> \\<br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -L$(call host-path, $(LOCAL_PATH)/../../cocos2dx/platform/third_party/android/libraries/$(TARGET_ARCH_ABI)) -lcurl</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	(Assuming the Box2D root directory is located in your cocos2d-x root directory.)</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	2. Modify ProjectName/android/jni/Android.mk as follows:</p>\n<p>\n	subdirs := $(addprefix $(LOCAL_PATH)/../../../,$(addsuffix /Android.mk, \\<br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; cocos2dx \\<br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; CocosDenshion/android \\<br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:#ffff00;\">&nbsp; Box2D \\</span><br>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;))</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	3. Modify ProjectName/android/jni/Application.mk as follows:</p>\n<p>\n	APP_MODULES := cocos2d cocosdenshion <span style=\"background-color:#ffff00;\">box2d</span> game_logic game</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	4. Run build_native script. When finished, you should see \"libbox2d.so\" under</p>\n<p>\n	ProjectName/android/libs/armeabi</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	The ndk docs are very helpful in understanding how to use ndk makefiles.</p>\n<p>\n	You may want to read OVERVIEW, ANDROID-MK, and APPLICATION-MK.</p>\n<p>\n	These documents are found in root_ndk/docs</p>',NULL,'@'),(251,'C',250,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,74,NULL,1651500030,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-25 18:08:34',NULL,NULL,'This didn\'t work.  It doesn\'t build the Box2D lib.  The files are included so it compiles, what I am getting is linking errors.\n\n\nC:\\cocos2d-1.0.1-x-0.11.0\\BreakoutBox2d\\android/jni/../../Classes/../../Box2D/Box2D/Collision/Shapes/b2EdgeShape.h:72: undefined reference to `vtable for b2EdgeShape\'\n\nI added -lbox2d to <PROJECT>/Classes/Android.mk but that throws an error because the library isn\'t being built.',NULL,'@'),(252,'C',250,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,38,NULL,411246587,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-25 18:22:54',NULL,NULL,'Try adding \"$(LOCAL_PATH)/../../\" (the directory that contains Box2D) to LOCAL_C_INCLUDES.\n\nAlso add \"-lGLESv1_CM\" to LOCAL_LDLIBS',NULL,'@'),(253,'C',250,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,38,NULL,411246587,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-25 18:35:34',NULL,NULL,'See the following forum thread for some other items to try. It seems that there is no single solution that works for everyone.\nhttp://www.cocos2d-x.org/boards/10/topics/3445',NULL,'@'),(254,'C',250,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,74,NULL,1651500030,74,1651500030,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-25 21:24:35','2012-02-25 22:24:07',NULL,'It worked when I moved the box2d in front of game_logic::\n\nAPP_MODULES := cocos2d cocosdenshion game_logic game box2d\n\nto\n\nAPP_MODULES := cocos2d cocosdenshion box2d game_logic game',NULL,'@'),(255,'C',250,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,30,NULL,1136270530,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-26 12:21:03',NULL,NULL,'Doesn\'t work for me.\nI downloaded the tweejump from google-code, created a new project, copied all the files into the project, made the above changes, but still get the error when I ran ./build_native:\n\n\nC:/Users/Ping/Desktop/cocos2d-1.0.1-x-0.11/tweejump2/android/jni/../../Classes/MainScene.h:47: undefined reference to `vtable for MainScene\'\nC:/Users/Ping/Desktop/cocos2d-1.0.1-x-0.11/tweejump2/android/jni/../../Classes/GameScene.h:5: undefined reference to `vtable for GameScene\'\n\nwhat is that mean?',NULL,'@'),(256,'C',250,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,74,NULL,1651500030,74,1651500030,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-26 12:27:23','2012-02-26 12:29:20',NULL,'Does it compile and fail in the linking stage?  It also looks like tweejump is an app not a library.',NULL,'@'),(257,'C',250,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,30,NULL,1136270530,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-26 14:17:20',NULL,NULL,'Yes, it is an app, linked from the assignment page. \nIt is solved now after I moved the box2d before game_logic and added all the classes in Classes\\Android.mk',NULL,'@'),(258,'Q',NULL,6,5,6,NULL,2,260,82,NULL,1204253516,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,1283313715,9,1.36669e+10,0,'html','2012-02-28 02:29:48',NULL,'How to adjust to multi resolution?','<p>\n	The most related articles I\'ve read about adjusting to multi resolution:</p>\n<p>\n	<a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://www.cocos2d-x.org/boards/10/topics/2100\">http://www.cocos2d-x.org/boards/10/topics/2100</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://www.cocos2d-x.org/projects/cocos2d-x/wiki/How_does_cocos2d-x_support_multi-resolution\">http://www.cocos2d-x.org/projects/cocos2d-x/wiki/How_does_cocos2d-x_support_multi-resolution</a></p>\n<p>\n	The second one told you that cocos2dx in android has a scale display mode, but did not tell you how to enable it.</p>\n<p>\n	I tried the method in article one, which is&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"color: rgb(72, 72, 72); font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n	\"...on android is \"scale display mode\", you can enable</p>\n<pre style=\"margin-top: 1em; margin-right: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1.6em; padding-top: 2px; padding-right: 2px; padding-bottom: 2px; padding-left: 0px; background-color: rgb(250, 250, 250); border-top-width: 1px; border-right-width: 1px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-left-width: 1px; border-top-style: solid; border-right-style: solid; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: solid; border-top-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-right-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-bottom-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); border-left-color: rgb(218, 218, 218); width: auto; overflow-x: auto; overflow-y: hidden;\">\n// line23 of YourGame/android/jni/helloworld/main.cpp\nview-&gt;create(480, 320);\n</pre>\n<div>\n	...</div>\n<div>\n	\"</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	It did not work for me.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Any one has suggestions?</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<p style=\"color: rgb(72, 72, 72); font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">\n	&nbsp;</p>','','@'),(259,'A',258,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,70,NULL,1195225568,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-28 03:51:18',NULL,NULL,'What is not working in your scenario when you enable that line? That is the correct way to set scale dispaly mode on android. Make sure you not manually specifiying the size of your sprites in your code. You can just do CCSprite::spriteWithFile(\"...\") and it would automatically set bounds for sprite based on file.',NULL,'@'),(260,'A',258,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,51,NULL,2184285158,NULL,NULL,1,0,1,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-29 14:20:57',NULL,NULL,'Here are some tips for adapting your contents to multiple resolutions dynamically:\n\n1. Always get and use the screen width information from CCDirector when you wants to draw something on the screen.\n\n//  s.width and s.height can be used to refer to the screen width & height after the function call below\n\n    CCSize s = CCDirector::sharedDirector()->getWinSize();\n\n2. When you need to refer to a position on the screen, derive it from the relative size/location of the screen. e.g.\n\n  moving_ball ->setPosition(ccp(3*s.width/4, 4*s.height/7));\n\n3. The ->setScale() method in CCSprite can also be used to adjust the size of a CCSprite in different resolutions. e.g.\n\n      moving_ball->setScale(0.75);',NULL,'@'),(261,'C',260,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,82,NULL,1204253516,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-29 21:44:18',NULL,NULL,'setScale() solved my problem visually. Yes by visually I mean it only looks fit the screen, but when the collision happens, the collision detector uses the original size. ( So when I scale down, I had this awesome invisible paddle:P)\n\nTo solve this, you actually need to set another size, which is the content size. you can call setContentSize(). \n\nhere\'s an example to scale:\n\nball_->setScale(g_scalefactor);\nball_->setContentSize(CCSizeMake(ball_->getContentSize().width*g_scalefactor, ball_->getContentSize().height*g_scalefactor));',NULL,'@'),(262,'A',228,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,51,NULL,1659637834,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-29 23:47:00',NULL,NULL,'The Python program provided in Indivisual Assignment 2 is a GUI application. It runs on WIndows, Mac OS X and Linux. But in order to run it in a remote terminal, you need to launch a local X server (e.g. XMing for Windows) and enable X forwarding when you run your ssh terminal. Maybe an easier solution is to download and install a copy of python locally.',NULL,'@'),(263,'A',234,6,5,6,NULL,0,NULL,51,NULL,1659637834,NULL,NULL,0,0,0,NULL,0,NULL,0,'','2012-02-29 23:49:09',NULL,NULL,'I hope the following answers on stackoverflow help.\n\n \n\nhttp://stackoverflow.com/questions/5179686/restoring-state-of-textview-after-screen-rotation',NULL,'@');
